# Fluff Date: 2026-02-21 18:24:59
overview:<p>The Starhawk is a 70-ton Clan heavy OmniMech developed by Clan Snow Raven in 2948 during the Golden Century. Born from an ingenious act of engineering improvisation that combined proven components from two existing designs, the Starhawk served as a capable heavy combatant in the Snow Raven touman for several decades before being phased out in favor of newer acquisitions. Though its production run was relatively limited compared to other heavy OmniMechs of its era, the Starhawk remains a notable example of Snow Raven resourcefulness and the modularity inherent in OmniMech technology.</p>
capabilities:<p>Built around a 350-rated XL fusion engine, the Starhawk achieves a top speed of 86 kilometers per hour, placing it among the faster heavy OmniMechs of its era. The chassis mounts 8.5 tons of ferro-fibrous armor, providing reasonable protection for its weight class while freeing tonnage for pod-mounted weaponry. Fourteen fixed double heat sinks manage thermal loads across configurations. The hybrid construction combining Timber Wolf lower-chassis mobility with a Hellbringer-derived torso gives the Starhawk a distinctive combat profile that blends speed with versatile pod capacity.</p><p>In its Primary configuration, the Starhawk carries a pair of Ultra Autocannon/10s mounted in each arm, delivering devastating medium-range firepower with the option for increased rate of fire at the risk of jamming. An SRM-6 launcher in the right torso supplements the ballistic payload at close range, while an Active Probe and ECM Suite housed in the left torso provide significant electronic warfare capability. This sensor package allows the Starhawk to detect hidden units while simultaneously disrupting enemy targeting systems, making the Prime configuration well-suited to aggressive reconnaissance-in-force operations.</p><p>The Starhawk's armor protection, while reasonable, falls short of heavier OmniMechs in its weight class, and the design's reliance on ammunition-dependent weapons across most configurations leaves it vulnerable in extended engagements where resupply is unavailable. The XL engine, while enabling the design's impressive speed, also increases the risk of a catastrophic kill from torso damage that a standard engine might survive.</p>
deployment:<p>The Primary configuration reflects Clan Snow Raven's doctrinal preference for information superiority, typically deploying as a command element in heavy reconnaissance Stars where its integrated sensor suite complements the offensive capability of accompanying OmniMechs. The Active Probe and ECM Suite grant the MechWarrior exceptional situational awareness and the ability to shield nearby Starmates from enemy electronics, while the heavy ballistic armament ensures the Starhawk can hold its own when engagement becomes unavoidable. Snow Raven Star Commanders favored this variant for independent operations where a single heavy 'Mech needed to both gather intelligence and deliver firepower without dedicated support.</p>
history:<p>The Starhawk's origins lie in Clan Snow Raven's characteristic resourcefulness. In 2948, the Ravens successfully won the Timber Wolf's leg actuator specifications in a Trial against Clan Wolf, one of many such exchanges of technology that characterized the competitive but cooperative nature of the Golden Century. Rather than attempt to replicate the entire Timber Wolf design, Snow Raven engineers recognized that the adaptability of OmniMech gyroscopes would allow them to combine components from different chassis. They paired the Timber Wolf's proven lower assembly with the torso structure of the Hellbringer, producing a new 70-ton OmniMech that entered service as the Starhawk.</p><p>Production was established at Industrial Complex Raven Alpha on Lum, one of Clan Snow Raven's primary Homeworld manufacturing centers. The Starhawk served the Raven touman through the latter decades of the Golden Century and into the Political Century that followed, providing a capable heavy OmniMech platform for a Clan that historically invested more heavily in aerospace and naval assets than ground forces. The design saw service during the various inter-Clan conflicts and Trials that marked this period, though the Snow Ravens' preference for avoiding large-scale ground engagements meant the Starhawk saw less sustained combat than contemporary designs fielded by more aggressive Clans.</p><p>The Starhawk's production run appears to have been relatively limited in duration. Records indicate the production line was active from approximately the Late Succession Wars era through the second phase of the Clan Invasion, after which production ceased. The most likely explanation is that the Snow Ravens phased out the Starhawk after acquiring the Summoner production line from Clan Ghost Bear, which offered a proven 70-ton OmniMech with a more established combat record and broader logistical support. With the Summoner filling the same weight class niche, maintaining a parallel production line for the Starhawk became unnecessary.</p><p>Despite its limited production history, the Starhawk represents an important example of the technological cross-pollination that defined the Golden Century. Its hybrid construction demonstrated the modularity inherent in OmniMech technology, a principle that would be exploited by other Clans in later centuries. Surviving Starhawks likely remained in second-line or solahma units as newer designs replaced them on the front lines, gradually fading from active service as attrition and parts scarcity took their toll.</p>
